It is a problem that OutOfMemoryErrors aren't reported. We had the same problem in bug #12988, where there was no indication of what the problem was.
(In reply to comment #10) > Knut Anders: Are we generating lots of Derby JDBC query classes here
No, we shouldn't be (we use prepared statements and dynamic parameters). And even if we did, that should not have caused OOME in the indexer, but rather in the Derby network server process.
> (I've also seen some comments about internalized Strings?)
Yes, we intern strings to save memory when we parse the ctags output, because of bug #809. I don't think we do anything like that in the history code.

Good catch, Jørgen!
The use of String.intern() reduces the total memory requirements, but it does so by storing data in permgen instead of on the heap. We could get similar space savings by maintaining a HashSet of file names while building the History object, and then we'd only use the heap.
The real problem here, though, is that the data structure we use require that we have the entire history in memory before we store it to disk. Fixing that is a bigger task, and we should track that in a separate bug report.
But for this particular bug, I think devising our own interning mechanism on top of a HashSet would suffice.
